"In you go."

        A shove, a stumble, and the heavy door slams shut behind you. If the room had been larger, the sound would
        have echoed. Instead, it just falls dead, intensifying even further the strange claustrophobia that suddenly
        engulfs you.

        Standing there, plunged into near darkness, you’re overwhelmed by a feeling wrapped in a word: "finality."
        You refuse to entertain that thought for long. One thing you’ve learned is that nothing in life is ever final,
        not even death. Doors that are shut can be opened again. Despite that, you begin to doubt the path that
        you've decided to follow. That doubt, as well, lasts only a moment.

        The cell is musty, with a hint of decay. The only sound is the slow, erratic patter of water dripping somewhere nearby.
        Then, suddenly, from beyond the walls, comes a faint scream of pain, brief but piercing.

        Tip: To explore, click words or phrases in the text above (for example, "walls", "door", "death", "erratic patter of water") or
        in the list below. You will be able to finish the story with only the words below, but to fully experience it, you should explore
        the main text as well to see where it leads you. If something looks interesting, click on it!

> room

          Stone walls. Metal bars. Light flickering chaotically from somewhere, as if oil lamps are burning just
          out of sight. It strikes of cliché. Do they make prisons like this anymore? Or have you been thrust
          into an anachronism, a relic of a distant past that someone took and hid and preserved just for those like you?

There are two beds, one on each side of the room, surrounding a large central window.

The right bed looks unused.

The left bed is clearly occupied.

> walls

          The walls are high and made of stone blocks, with rough, uneven faces. There are numerous holes dotting the surface.
          It’s unclear whether they’re intentional or just the result of careless craftsmanship.

        As you look, a dark shape scurries to one and disappears into its depths.

> beds
There are two beds, one on each side of the room, surrounding a large central window.

The right bed looks unused.

The left bed is clearly occupied.

> left bed

          In the half light, you make out a figure on the left bed, propped up in the corner. The
          eyes are large, larger than seem normal. They shift in your direction and then away. You're not sure
          if it's out of curiosity or fear. There’s no other movement - just quiet study.

> figure
 • Look at the strange figure
 • Talk to the strange figure

        Tip: This topic has more than one possibility. Select a choice by clicking it.
        These menus are optional, so feel free to select something else if you don't like what you see.

> 1

          Fear catches your breath as you look closer. Thin and gaunt with a hairless head and those huge eyes,
          it looks like some malevolent mythical creature - and you’re trapped in a room with it.
          Perhaps this is meant to be your final punishment.

The light shifts, and you blink in confusion. A sudden flicker illuminates the corner, and you see it’s
        actually an old man. Such weary eyes... Thin and frail, his tattered garments hang on skin and bones.
        You imagine he’s been here quite a long time. Then the realization hits you,
        and you're sickened as you gaze at what might well be your own future.

> old man
 • Look at the old man
 • Talk to the old man
> 2

        There's too much tension in the room, too much unsettled. It's time to assert some level of
        control over the situation, or you’ll go mad.

        You raise a hand tentatively. “Hello.”

          The old man regards you with an empty smile. His voice croaks. "Indeed."

> old man
 • Look at the old man
 • Ask the old man about himself
 • Ask the old man about prison
> 2
"Who are you," you say, "if I may ask?"

          He's silent for so long, you think he's ignoring you. Then he seems to come to a decision. "My name is Spon."

          He inclines his head in your direction. "And what might your name be?"

 • Tell him your name
 • Make up a name
> 1
You tell him your name.

"Well met," he says, with a slight bow of his head. "If only it were under better circumstances."
> Spon
 • Look at Spon
 • Ask Spon about prison
 • Ask Spon why he's here
> 2
You take in your surroundings with a sweep of your hand. "What is this place?"
"Have you ever heard of Colintha?" he asks.

          The room sways. “Colintha.” It's a word whispered when it's spoken at all. Everyone has heard the legend of a place so abhorrent,
          so terrifying, so anathema to the human soul that most cannot believe it even exists. Discussion is discouraged; details
          are scarce. More than definitive thought, it invokes what can best be described as a feeling, one beyond dread, beyond fear.
          It has its roots in the darkest nightmares. It is all that's wrong with the world.

          He watches you in silence, awaiting your reply. You manage to find your voice.

 • Reply yes
 • Reply no
> 1
With a nod, you say, "I've heard legends of a secret prison more terrible than anyone dares imagine."

          "This is that place."

> Colintha
"Can you tell me more about Colintha?"

          "All I can tell you is what I have experienced myself in this cell, along with what I've gleaned from those who have
          shared it with me during my time here." He pauses before continuing on.

          "Colintha is a prison for only the worst of the Empire's enemies. All here pose a direct and serious threat to the Empire's existence,
          whether it be a physical threat or even just a spiritual one. Regardless, nobody sent here has ever returned home.

          "What's more, the place itself seems beyond technology, beyond magic. I don't know what wizardry has gone into its construction,
          but the walls defy any attempts at destruction, the creatures that live here..." He gestures all around the room.
          "...are distorted and fantastical,  and the place itself has a regenerative property which, ironically, prolongs life
          in those who least wish it."

> Spon
 • Look at Spon
 • Ask Spon why he's here
> 2
"Why are you here? What was your crime?"

          The bitterness is clear in his voice. "My 'crime' was promoting justice. My 'sin' was caring more about the citizens of the empire
          than about the Emperor himself or his ambitions or his decrees." He leans forward. “I was young and idealistic and bubbling
          with a naive hubris, ignorant of how the world actually works.” After a moment's silence: “I'm no longer naive. I've learned lessons
          that, in a better world, no one should have to."

          He shifts on the bed, his gaze beyond the room. "More painful than being in this place is the almost daily torture of thoughts - of my young child
          whose father never came home, of my beloved wife whose beloved husband suddenly disappeared after just a few short years of marriage.
          Of them not knowing where I am, whether I'm alive. Of me not knowing the same about them. All in the name of 'civil stability' or
          whatever they call it these days."

> wife
"Tell me about your wife."

With surprising agility, he slides from the corner to the edge of the bed. "Let me show you."
          Cupping his hands, he closes his eyes and relaxes. You wonder what he's doing. Then, with a flash, an image bursts
          into existence above his upturned hands, bathed in blue fire.

        Long, wispy hair. Gentle eyes. A smile filled with affection and a hint of mischief. It's a snapshot
        floating in the air before you, brightening the room with more than just its magical light.

> child
Spon is too occupied to hear you.

        The view pans back to reveal an opulent garden. A fruit tree casts shade on flowering shrubs, and a small, two-person bench beckons.
        She stands waiting. For a moment, you feel she might be looking at you.

> window

          The one part of the room offering a hope of escape is the tall window between the beds, running all
          the way to the ceiling. Even that hope is slight, given the mesh of heavy bars across it.

          It's sunset outside, painting the sky with a deep, sanguine tint. Lovely in a depraved sort of way,
          it only makes the room darker.

        Perhaps during the day, the window will look out
        onto luscious green hills, a crystal-clear stream, and birds flying free in an open sky. Such a sight
        would be a welcome change from the dreariness of the room but, at the same time, a tease beyond reach.

        Words form silently in her mouth and then a broad smile. She reaches out her hand just as the image fades.

A great sigh shakes him as he turns to you. His eyes shine in the dim light.
 "You can't imagine how much I miss her."

> door

        The door seems less a door than a section of movable wall. There must be magic in this place
        to allow something so large and heavy to move with such ease. Now that it’s shut, it’s as if
        someone has simply painted a thin, dark, door-shaped outline onto the stone. No light enters around it.
        There's no handle. It’s cold to the touch, hard and impersonal, and so solid
        that you could pound as hard as you might, and no one would ever hear you.

> scream
You've heard screams before, but none like this. It was the sound of someone strong pushed to the breaking point.
      It was agonized and visceral. It was the sound of defeat.
> holes

          The more you study the holes, the less you want to. There’s no rhyme or reason to them – some are
          up high, some are near the beds, and there are even some directly overhead in the ceiling. They’re
          all shadow just below the surface, but there’s disturbing movement everywhere you look,
          with dark shapes writhing, just visible, inside the openings. You know that what
          goes in can come out – and you have to sleep sometime.

Spon sees you looking at the holes. "Be sure not to put your hand in there. You might not get it back."
> ceiling

          The ceiling overhead is stone, like the walls. There are large webs in the corner, far too
          high to clear away. Given the size of the spiders needed to make them, you realize that’s probably a good thing.

> child
"Tell me about your child."

He joins his hands again, and another image appears.

        It's a scene inside someone's home, showing a room with no small amount of clutter.  Overflowing bookcases,
        scattered furniture, hiding places... A small face peers from a recess, watching, waiting. Then, arms raised, fingers curled, she springs, mouth wide
        in a shout but never concealing her smile. A burst of laughter, and then she is running, dodging, chased, heading for the outside door and the wide world.

> webs

        These are not your average garden webs. Woven with thick strands, they sit like fishing nets in the corners.
        Only the irregular construction and familiar circular patterns hint at their true nature.

        A ball rolls across the ground with a small child walking behind, foot extending out from time to time to
        keep it moving on its way. Her hair is long; her dress is petite, with a handmade quality. A kick too hard, and the ball moves out
        of sight, with the girl running after.

> window
Through the bars covering the window, you can gaze longingly out on the world.
The sky is gradually growing darker.

        The scene shifts once more, and she is standing there, looking up at you shyly before looking away. Her mouth moves
        in silent jabber, words still strange and new brought forth with precise concentration. A pause, and then she steps forward and reaches up with both hands.

        With that, the image disappears, and the room is dark once more.
He wipes a tear from his cheek.

        "She was almost three. She'll be a young woman now. I've missed her growing up. I've missed everything."

> scream
The scream echoes in your mind, a new and unwanted memory.
> room

          Stone walls. Metal bars. Light flickering chaotically from somewhere, as if oil lamps are burning just
          out of sight.

There are two beds, one on each side of the room, surrounding a large central window.

The right bed looks unused.

Spon is sitting on the left bed.

            Spon shifts on the bed and takes from his pocket a cloth-wrapped package. Carefully undoing it, he
            removes what appears to be a small, hand-rolled cigarette. He looks at you and holds it up. "Smoke?"

 • Yes, please
 • Maybe later
 • No thanks
> 1

          You've never wanted something more. "They took mine away." Seeing the need in your eye, he tosses it to you, takes one for himself
          and lights them both. You take a long drag and let it out slowly. "You're a lifesaver." The aroma is unusual, a blend you're
          not familiar with.

            He gestures to your bed. "Why not take a load off while you can?"

> right bed
 • Examine right bed
 • Sit on the right bed
> 2
You sit on the empty bed. From this new vantage, you notice some odd writing on the wall.

The smoke from your cigarettes mixes in the air.
It has a sweet smell. You find it relaxing in an unusual way.
> writing

        In the corner, someone has carved a message in the stone. You
        can barely make out the first part - it’s etched in simple strokes: XYZZY. Below that single
        faded word, nearly lost to the progress of time, the rest is clearer:

        "Little by little, the chains fell away. One by one, the locks were wrenched off and cast aside. After decades
        of looking at the same walls, the doors were opened, the crumbling edifice was abandoned, and they
        staggered out into the promise of a new day. They drew in the crisp, fresh air and felt the warmth
        of the sun. With sudden laughter, they fell down and rolled in the grass and then lay breathless,
        looking up at a wide open sky. And having broken free of the shackles that had bound them for so
        long, they soon discovered with great delight that they could fly."

> window
Through the bars covering the window, you can gaze longingly out on the world.
The sky is gradually growing darker.
> scream
Your mind keeps returning to that awful sound. Such dwelling will lead to madness. You try to turn your thoughts to something new.
> decay

        The smell triggers an unwanted memory... It was the first rain after the great destruction.
        There were still bodies in the streets, or what bits remained of them - too much to pick up. You tried despite the intensity of your grieving, but it was just too much.
        The raindrops fell like tears at first, a gentle lamentation over the village. Then it turned to a downpour, washing the stench of death into every nook and cranny. In the weeks that followed, all you
        could do was pray it would some day fade away on its own. It never did.

          Spon takes a long, final drag on his cigarette before extinguishing it.

> doubt
You often wonder if these doubts that you banish so quickly are mere distractions to be ignored - or the voice of your conscience.

Though the cigarette you hold might be the last for a while, it's making your head swim. You grind it out but pocket the stub.

Spon leans forward. "I suppose if we're going to be sharing a room, I should know at least something about you. Who did you offend to end up in this place?"

          It's the question you've been dreading. The past few days have been a nightmare of threats, beatings, and drugs.
          Despite all of that, the interrogators were no match for your discipline and determination. You're so used to the
          struggle, so used to saying nothing to anyone, that you almost can't imagine opening up now. The 'almost' in that
          thought is because of the old man himself. There is something about him that's calm and reassuring. Safe. Secure. And
          goodwill may be in short supply for the foreseeable future.

 • Tell the truth.
 • Be vague.
 • Lie.
> 1

          You wonder if the old man has  worked some kind of magic on you. Despite your reservations, you find yourself opening up.
          "I was arrested for 'being a spy and committing acts of sabotage.'"

He leans forward with interest. "What did you do?"

          A certain intensity in his question raises a tiny alarm. You're not sure if the feeling is something real
          or just a result of what you've been through lately.

 • Tell him
 • Be vague
 • Lie
> 1

          The words form in your mind, but they just won't come out. You feel an odd comfort with this man,
          but something inside is rising up in protest, holding your tongue. Resigned to the inevitable,
          you say instead, "I'd rather not talk about that."

> window
Through the bars covering the window, you can gaze longingly out on the world.
The sky is gradually growing darker.
> scream
Your mind keeps returning to that awful sound. Such dwelling will lead to madness. You try to turn your thoughts to something new.
> walls

          The walls are high and made of stone blocks, with rough, uneven faces. There are numerous holes dotting the surface.
          It’s unclear whether they’re intentional or just the result of careless craftsmanship.

"What about you?" Spon asks. "You have any family or anyone out there who will be missing you?"

A wave of emotions makes the room dim. Thoughts normally kept at bay surge forward, infesting your mind like so many crawly things.
          They itch and pinch and wriggle. You want to reach inside and rip them out, but like always, they're beyond reach. More suppression,
          and they'll go away, pushed back below the surface. Or perhaps it's time to let them out somehow.

 • Tell him
 • Be vague
 • Lie
> 1

          "I was married," you say, anger creeping into your voice. "And I had a son. They're both dead now, along with many in my village, victims
          of this so-called 'emperor'. It was all so pointless..." Your eyes meet as you try to pour all your emotion into him.
          "My life ended the day they were killed. This madness must end!" You watch him, wondering if you've gone too far.

The next question is not unexpected.

"What happened?"
 • Open up
 • Avoid the question
> 1
It hits you all over again as you bring forth the words. "I was walking in the hills that day, high above our home." You turn to him.
        "It was just a normal day, nothing special, no hint of anything. I was watching them down there, the two of them, laughing, playing together..."
        A smile creeps onto your face. It abruptly vanishes. "Then from from the sky, something like fire..." You almost can't speak. "Great
        burning balls that fell all over the village, obliterating everything in their path." For a moment, you're no longer in the cell,
        but someplace much, much worse. You don't even see him any more. "One landed... I saw... They were just..."

He's silent for a while. "I'm sorry for your loss."
 • Respond angrily
 • Thank him
 • Say nothing
> 2
"Thank you."
> window
Through the bars covering the window, you can gaze longingly out on the world.
The sky is gradually growing darker.
> scream
Your mind keeps returning to that awful sound. Such dwelling will lead to madness. You try to turn your thoughts to something new.
> beds
There are two beds, one on each side of the room, surrounding a large central window.

You are sitting on the right bed.

Spon is sitting on the left bed.

A low pure tone begins...

        The contrast to the silent calm startles you. The tone continues and deepens,
        as if the walls themselves were moaning in sorrow. The prickles of fear this stirs seem
        founded as a chorus soon joins in, with muffled voices from all around in the prison raised in wails and screams.
        There is something else as well, a sound from a nightmare.

        From the walls, there is the slush of things suddenly moving, shifting, scurrying, swarming. The holes begin
        to vomit streams of black life, emerging and spreading out across the surface, covering everything in sight.
        As they reach the floor, instinct moves you up onto the bed, a gesture that you know is probably hopeless. Great ebony insects with
        pincers, ribbed pills with antennae curiously testing the air, long millipedes snaking over the writhing mass – those and more clamber to go
        somewhere, anywhere besides the holes where they previously rested.

          There's more fear in your voice than you wish. "What's going on?"

          His response is simple but chilling. "Feeding time."

        Intensifying the nightmare, you begin to sense movement above you, along the ceiling.

> ceiling

            A sound above draws your gaze, and you collapse back onto the bed. Great bulbous things
            (you hesitate to call them spiders),
            with bodies the size of a man's torso and long angled legs, drag themselves from recesses
            above to take their places in the webs, one directly over each bed. They sit motionless,
            waiting, sometimes spinning slightly, sometimes darting out with legs to entrap whatever comes near.
            Their legs are pointed and covered in coarse hair, as are their bodies.

        Spon grabs a beetle off the wall and bites it in half with an unsettling, spurting crunch.
He drags a hand across his mouth. "Better grab what you can," he says, chewing casually. "This is all we get to eat."

> walls

          The walls teem with anxious, restless life. The creatures that have poured forth from the scattered holes now cover its surface.

> bugs
 • Look at bugs
 • Catch bug
> 2

        You reach into the great moving mass on the wall and grab hold of the first thing you can. It's a hard, black beetle
        struggling in your grasp, its legs clawing at the air.

> bugs
 • Look at bugs
 • Eat bug
> 2

        If only the thing would stop moving. You contemplate just shoving it all in at once, but the
        thought that it might somehow remain alive inside you makes you reconsider. Slipping it half way into your mouth,
        you pause for strength. Its legs dance across your tongue and the inside of your lips. It's all too much.
        Closing your eyes, you bite down. There's a crack that makes you cringe and then a bitter, sticky liquid squirts
        along your tongue and part way down your throat. You fight a gag as you begin to chew.

        Eventually, you manage to swallow, despite all the hard bits that remain. Then you swallow again. And again.
        And finally it's all the way down. One half to go... At least what's left is no longer moving. You shove it in and bite down,
        and the bitterness doubles. You wonder if there's some sort of acid in these creatures - or any nutrients whatsoever.

> bugs
 • Look at bugs
 • Catch bug
> 2
Not quite believing this is happening, you reach out again and come away with another scurrying thing.
> spiders
Spiders... Why did it have to be spiders?

        "What are those?" you ask, holding back the expletives that would have summed up your emotional state. You point to the ceiling.

        He stares vacantly at a spot just below your bed. "We call them 'tormentors.'"

Suddenly, there comes a most inhuman sound. It's the cry of a bird of prey mixed with the snarl of a large cat, long, drawn-out, terrifying.
          It echoes in the tiny room.

            Looking up, you see that the spider above Spon has left its web and is dangling in air now on a slender strand,
            slowly descending straight for him.

> spiders

        The name "tormentors" has implications you'd prefer not to contemplate, but you have no choice.
        Primary among them is that these creatures might have a definite purpose, one you're not looking forward to experiencing.

        "Why are they called 'tormentors?'"

        "Because every night, just after the sun goes down, they come out and torment us. It's part of our punishment.
        You'll discover soon enough a new level of pain. They will rip you apart but not kill you. And then you'll heal
        just in time for it to start all over again the following sunset. You begin to pray for death."

> walls

          The walls teem with anxious, restless life. The creatures that have poured forth from the scattered holes now cover its surface.

The spider is now half way to Spon. It shrieks again, hairs surrounding its beak-like mouth undulating fiercely
            in the blast of air.

> holes
The holes are almost indistinguishable now from what has come out of them. You know they're there somewhere,
        buried under the mass of writhing black, but they don't seem to matter much any more.
> window
Looking out the window, you see the sun has set.

The spider is just above Spon now.
> ceiling
The spider above Spon is lowering slowly on a strand. The other sits idly in its web above you, waiting.
> walls

          The walls teem with anxious, restless life. The creatures that have poured forth from the scattered holes now cover its surface.

The spider hovers above Spon. He sits there passively as its legs spread wide, their sharp tips poised to strike.
> holes
The holes are almost indistinguishable now from what has come out of them. You know they're there somewhere,
        buried under the mass of writhing black, but they don't seem to matter much any more.
> window
Looking out the window, you see the sun has set.

The spider's legs suddenly thrust inward, heading toward him. You're surprised how quickly they move. You want to reach out, to fight, to scream, anything,
            but all you can do is sit, immobilized by shock and fear. They seem to take forever to get to him. Your mind races ahead, imagining horrific scenarios.
            Then at the last moment, the legs snap to a halt. They're so close, you're not sure at first if they've hit him, but then you see the gaps,
            the mere inches that have spared him.

The spider slowly spreads its legs wide once more, almost reluctantly, and begins inching its way back up toward its
          nest in the ceiling.

> ceiling
The creature hadn't attacked Spon as you thought it would. You need to know why.

        "Why didn't it attack you?"

        "They may seem hideous to you," he says, "but there is nothing purely evil, just as there is nothing purely good.
        Such extremes exist only in the minds of those lacking the ability to comprehend the complexities of the Universe.
        Those that built this place..." His hand sweeps the room; then he points up. "...also created the tormentors. But in
        giving them the intelligence needed to creatively rip men apart, they also quite accidentally imparted to them
        logic and a deep sense of justice. The Empire may never let us leave here, but the tormentors do not have to abide by the
        Emperor's wishes that we suffer needlessly."

        He looks straight at you. "To avoid their wrath, you must repent. You must abandon your hatred and liberate yourself
        of your crime. And you must do it honestly and sincerely. They know what's in our hearts."

> repent
"You said I have to repent. What does that mean?"

        "You must acknowledge your crime," he says, "declaring what you have done and then expressing sincere remorse for your transgression."

          He shifts on the bed. "For example," he continues, "you told me your crime was sabotage, but
you held back the details
.
          You must declare all about your offense for the tormentors to leave you in peace."

The spider continues its ascent.
> sabotage

            You're not sure why, but you've developed a certain trust for this strange old man.

            And your time in this cell has made you contemplate what you've done. Did your thirst for revenge blind you to what was right?

He hasn't stopped looking at you. "So... what will it be?"
 • Repent
 • Refuse
> 1

            With a great sigh, you decide it's time to cast off your burden. It has only led you to this horrible place.
            Enough people have died.

            "I've placed a bomb in the Emperor's city." For a moment, you pause as the words "capitol city" flash
            in your mind. Where did those come from? "It's located near the palace, in a place I knew would be crowded
            when it went off. I hope you can understand – I'm not normally evil or destructive or hateful.
            But what they did to my family..." You look out the window and wish you were there. "I've become them.
            Someone needs to stop it before it's too late."

            Spon looks at you and smiles, as a blinding light grows from all around, making the room, the spiders and the old man disappear...

